{
  "doc_id": "52313",
  "text": "The one difference from previous midlatitude results which is surprising is the absence of a temporary growth phase. [CITATION_1] has argued that for a midlatitude disturbance, the wave will amplify at the expense of the mean flow for a finite time, perhaps growing by many orders of magnitude if the zonal scale is very large in comparison to the latitudinal scale, before succumbing to the inevitable asymptotic decay. Strictly speaking, this argument only applies to plane waves with an initial tilt against the shear (that is, with lines of constant phase running NW SE if dU/dy > 0), but [CITATION_2] fig. 2 ) shows that if we superimpose two such components, one tilted against the shear and one tilted with the shear so that their sum is proportional to cos(my), the tilted-against wave will still amplify, and may dominate the large time disturbance since the other component is decaying.",
